\f0\b\fs60 \cf2 Task 1. Hello world\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In Cloud Shell enter the following command to run a hello world container to get started:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
docker run hello-world\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This simple container returns\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 Hello from Docker!
\f1\fs32 \cb3 \'a0to your screen. While the command is simple, notice in the output the number of steps it performed. The Docker daemon searched for the hello-world image, didn't find the image locally, pulled the image from a public registry called Docker Hub, created a container from that image, and ran the container for you.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Run the following command to take a look at the container image it pulled from Docker Hub:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
docker images\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This is the image pulled from the Docker Hub public registry. The Image ID is in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/sha256.html"}}{\fldrslt SHA256 hash}}\'a0format\'97this field specifies the Docker image that's been provisioned. When the Docker daemon can't find an image locally, it will by default search the public registry for the image.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Run the container again:\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb1 \
docker run hello-world\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Notice the second time you run this, the Docker daemon finds the image in your local registry and runs the container from that image. It doesn't have to pull the image from Docker Hub.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Finally, look at the running containers by running the following command:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 docker ps\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 There are no running containers. You already exited the hello-world containers you previously ran.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In order to see all containers, including ones that have finished executing, run\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 docker ps -a
\f1\fs32 \cb3 :\cb1 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
docker ps -a\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This shows you the\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 Container ID
\f1\fs32 \cb3 , a UUID generated by Docker to identify the container, and more metadata about the run. The container\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 Names
\f1\fs32 \cb3 \'a0are also randomly generated but can be specified with\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 docker run --name [container-name] hello-world
\f1\fs32 \cb3 .\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs60 \cf2 Task 2. Build\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 In this section, you will build a Docker image that's based on a simple node application.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Execute the following command to create and switch into a folder named\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 test
\f1\fs32 \cb3 .\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 mkdir test && cd test\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Create a\'a0
\f3\fs30 \cb4 Dockerfile
\f1\fs32 \cb3 :\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
cat > Dockerfile <<EOF\
# Use an official Node runtime as the parent image\
FROM node:lts\
\
# Set the working directory in the container to /app\
WORKDIR /app\
\
# Copy the current directory contents into the container at /app\
ADD . /app\
\
# Make the container's port 80 available to the outside world\
EXPOSE 80\
\
# Run app.js using node when the container launches\
CMD ["node", "app.js"]\
EOF\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This file instructs the Docker daemon on how to build your image.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The initial line specifies the base parent image, which in this case is the official Docker image for node version long term support (lts).\cb1 \
\ls9\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In the second, you set the working (current) directory of the container.\cb1 \
\ls9\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In the third, you add the current directory's contents (indicated by the\'a0
